[REASON:planning] <physical_use>
[REASON:planning]   <orientation>The part rests flat on the XY print bed. The bottom of the VESA plate (Z=0) and the bottom of the front tray lip (Z=0) form a continuous flat contact surface against the table or monitor stand.</orientation>
[REASON:planning]   <contact_surfaces>The primary contact face is the combined bottom plane at Z=0, spanning approximately 240mm (X) by 180mm (Y). All other geometry extends upward from Z=0. The laptop base contacts the tilted tray surface and the front/side lips.</contact_surfaces>
[REASON:planning]   <applied_forces>Gravity pulls the laptop (~1.5kg) straight down. Due to the 30-degree tilt, a forward sliding force component acts along the tray surface toward the user. The front lip resists this forward force. The diagonal struts and gussets resist the bending moment and shear forces transferring the load back to the vertical VESA plate.</contact_surfaces>
[REASON:planning]   <containment_strategy>The front retention lip (15mm high) and side lips (10mm high) physically block the laptop from sliding off the tilted surface. Friction between the laptop base and the tray surface, combined with the lip geometry, provides secure containment under normal typing or viewing loads.</containment_strategy>
[REASON:planning]   <pose_intent>The tray_base, tray_front_lip, tray_side_lips, gussets, and hex_cutouts are all tilted -30 degrees around the X-axis relative to horizontal. The VESA plate and struts remain axis-aligned or use their own specific rotation tags. No compound rotations are used.</pose_intent>
[REASON:planning]   <use_cycle>User mounts the VESA plate to a monitor or wall bracket using M4 screws. User places the laptop onto the tilted tray. The laptop slides slightly forward until it contacts the front lip, then remains stationary during use.</use_cycle>
[REASON:planning]   <ergonomic_notes>The 30-degree tilt raises the laptop screen to a more comfortable viewing angle, reducing neck strain. The front lip is low enough to allow easy placement but high enough to prevent accidental bumps from knocking the laptop off. Side lips prevent lateral drift.</ergonomic_notes>
[REASON:planning]   <mating_object>Standard 13-14 inch laptop or tablet with keyboard case. Approximate footprint 300x210mm, but the tray is sized to 240x200mm to fit the print volume while accommodating smaller devices or leaving edge clearance for larger ones. VESA 75x75mm mounting pattern on the back of a monitor.</mating_object>
[REASON:planning] </physical_use>
[REASON:planning] <feature_decisions>
[REASON:planning]   <decision feature="fasteners_or_mounting_holes" needed="true">VESA mounting holes are explicitly required to attach the bracket to a monitor or wall mount.</decision>
[REASON:planning]   <decision feature="internal_cavity_or_shell" needed="false">The tray is a solid 5mm plate with hex cutouts for weight reduction; a full shell cavity is unnecessary and would complicate printing without significant material savings.</decision>
[REASON:planning]   <decision feature="retention_geometry" needed="true">Front and side lips are required to prevent the laptop from sliding off the 30-degree tilted surface under gravity.</decision>
[REASON:planning]   <decision feature="load_bearing_reinforcement" needed="true">Diagonal struts and thickened gusset junctions are explicitly included to resist bending moments and distribute load from the tray to the VESA plate.</decision>
[REASON:planning]   <decision feature="clearance_or_port_cutouts" needed="false">No specific cable ports or hand-access cutouts were requested; the open tray design inherently allows access to laptop ports.</decision>
[REASON:planning]   <decision feature="moving_or_mating_interface" needed="false">The design is a static mount; no hinges, threads, or sliding mechanisms are required beyond the standard VESA screw interface.</decision>
